subsection.p:
Recall that in Theorem  we defined  S(x)=\alpha\,f(x)+\beta\,g(x), where \alpha,\beta\in\bbbr  are constants. We wish to compute S'(x), so we start with the definition:


  S'(x) &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{S(x+h)-S(x)}{h}


Let us concentrate on the numerator of the expression inside the limit and then come  back to the full limit in a moment. Substitute in the definition of S(x):


  S(x+h)-S(x) &=
  \big[ \alpha f(x+h) + \beta g(x+h) \big] -
  \big[ \alpha f(x) + \beta g(x) \big]  &\text{collect terms}

&=\alpha\big[f(x+h)-f(x)]+\beta\big[g(x+h)-g(x)\big]


Now it is easy to see the structures we need  namely, we almost have the expressions  for the derivatives f'(x) and g'(x). Indeed, all we need to do is divide by h and  take the limit. So lets finish things off.


  S'(x) &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{S(x+h)-S(x)}{h} & \text{from above}

  &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\alpha\big[f(x+h)-f(x)]+\beta\big[g(x+h)-g(x)\big] }{h}

  &= \lim_{h \to 0} \left[ \alpha\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} + \beta\frac{g(x+h)-g(x)}{h}
\right] &\text{limit laws}

  &= \alpha\lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} + \beta\lim_{h\to0}\frac{g(x+h)-g(x)}{h}

  &=\alpha f'(x) + \beta g'(x)


as required.

This one is relatively messy, so we have made it optional. Let us start by writing the  quotient of our two functions as Q(x) = f(x) / g(x), and we assume that g(x) \neq 0.  As before, we start our manipulations from the definition of the derivative


Q'(x)
&=\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{Q(x+h)-Q(x)}{h} && \text{(now substitute in $Q$)}

& =\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{1}{h}
           \left[\frac{f(x+h)}{g(x+h)}-\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}\right] &&
\text{(and then form a common denominator)}

&=\lim_{h\to 0}
    \frac{ f(x+h)\cdot g(x) - f(x)\cdot g(x+h) }
                            {h \cdot g(x+h)\cdot g(x)}


We make use of the same F, G that we used in the proof of the product rule. We use  them to rewrite f(x+h) as f(x) + hF(h) and g(x+h) as g(x+h)=g(x)+hG(h).  First  concentrate on the numerator of the above expression:


f(x+h)\cdot g(x) - f(x)\cdot g(x+h)
&=[f(x)+hF(h)]\cdot g(x) - f(x)\cdot [g(x)+hG(h)]

&=f(x)\cdot g(x) + h g(x) \cdot F(h)  -f(x)\cdot g(x) - h f(x) \cdot G(h)

&= h g(x) \cdot F(h)  - h f(x) \cdot G(h)


So dividing this by the denominator, and cancelling the common factor  of h, gives


\frac{Q(x+h)-Q(x)}{h}
  &= \frac{F(h) \cdot g(x) - f(x)\cdot G(h)}{g(x+h)\cdot g(x)}


To arrive at Q'(x) we take the limit of the above as h \to 0; since it  is the limit of a ratio with a non-zero denominator, the result is a ratio  of limits:


Q'(x)
&=\lim_{h\to 0}
\frac{F(h) \cdot g(x) - f(x)\cdot G(h)}{g(x+h)\cdot g(x)}

&=
\frac{\ds \lim_{h\to 0} \left[ F(h) \cdot g(x) - f(x)\cdot G(h)\right]}
{\ds \lim_{h \to 0} \left[ g(x+h)\cdot g(x)\right]}


Processing the denominator gives


\lim_{h \to 0} \left[ g(x+h)\cdot g(x)\right]
&= g(x) \cdot \lim_{h\to0}g(x+h) & \text{since $g(x)$ doesn't change with $h$}

&= g(x)^2


While the numerator is


\lim_{h\to 0} \left[ F(h) \cdot g(x) - f(x)\cdot G(h)\right]
&= \lim_{h\to0} F(h)\cdot g(x) - \lim_{h\to 0} f(x)\cdot G(h)

Now because f(x),g(x) do not change with h we can factor them  out.

&= g(x) \lim_{h\to0} F(h) - f(x) \lim_{h\to 0} G(h)

&= g(x) f'(x) - f(x) g'(x)


Putting these pieces back together finally gives


Q(x) &= \frac{g(x) f'(x) - f(x) g'(x)}{g(x)^2}.


And we arrive at the quotient rule. Note that we have assumed that the  derivatives f'(x), g'(x) exist and that g(x) \neq 0.
